<h3>For writers</h3>

<h4>What's collected?</h4>

<p>
  See everything above, plus some of this as well:
</p>

<ul>
  <li>
    <strong>Personal data</strong>: information that has the possibility
    of identifying you in itself or with other data. Examples are the username (handle)
    and password, which currently is all we track. Personal data is 
    defined in the General Data Protection Regulation.
  </li>

  <li>
    <strong>Technical data</strong>: data that comes from a technical source, usually
    stemming in some way from your browser. Technical data can snowball into personal
    data because it can result in someone discovering your username/password.
  </li>
</ul>

<p>
  As a writer we need to be able to authenticate you because we only want experts
  writing articles. A HTTP
  <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTTP_cookie">cookie</a> is how we do that.
  It's something that's stored temporarily and then gets deleted whenever you logout
  or after a certain period of time. It's not persisted beyond those two things.
</p>

<h4>Why is it collected?</h4>

<p>
  Site functionality, compliance with the law when applicable, and troubleshooting
  when applicable. We feel morally obligated to not take the same path as many
  other companies have, like Google or Facebook, in taking user data and brokering
  it out.
</p>

